<DOCNO> AP890107-0014 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a program that included paid work leaves and 
avoiding physical exertion cut the premature birth rate at a french 
hospital by a third but its costeffectiveness is debatable 
researchers say 
participants could take longer leaves than the sixweek paid 
leave available to french women before their due date said 
researcher emile papiernik 
for example a woman whose job involved a lot of standing might 
begin the leave 10 weeks before the due date said papiernik 
chairman of the obstetrics and gynecology department at the 
university of paris south 
the program also included teaching women to avoid physically 
taxing situations at home like moving a household and to follow 
such steps as sitting rather than standing when washing clothes 
papiernik said friday in an interview 
it also stressed close relationships with caregivers he said 
the overall goal was to reduce physical exertion that triggers the 
uterus to contract during pregnancy 
a study of more than 16000 deliveries at the hospital found that 
while premature deliveries stood at 54 percent of live births for 
197174 they decreased to 36 percent for 197982 
the study could not demonstrate statistically that work leaves 
themselves made a difference but they probably helped papiernik 
wrote in a book about the research 
but an american expert said the french approach would incur 
inappropriate and unnecessary costs in the united states because 
most participants would have had fullterm pregnancies anyway 
most women at risk for premature births carry their fetuses to 
term and physicians cannot predict with great accuracy who will 
deliver prematurely said paul macdonald of the university of texas 
southwestern medical center in dallas 
macdonald also said many women may not want to pass up economic 
and psychological benefits of working 
he and papiernik spoke at a seminar sponsored by the march of 
dimes birth defects foundation 
some 350000 american babies every year are born more than three 
weeks before the end of the normal 40week term the foundation 
says they account for 70 percent of infant deaths and are at risk 
for such problems as cerebral palsy seizure disorders mental 
retardation and impairments of vision and hearing 
</TEXT>
