once a familiar figure who often accompanied emperor 
hirohito in his travels empress nagako in recent years has been 
confined to a wheelchair and seldom makes public appearances 
the 85yearold empress married hirohito who died saturday 
nearly 65 years ago and would have celebrated her anniversary later 
this month 
born march 6 1903 nagako was the daughter of imperial prince 
kuniyoshi kuni she was brought up in tokyo attending the elite 
peers school for girls 
she later received instruction from two american quakers 
elizabeth vining and esther rhoads who were credited with inspiring 
many of the democratic changes which permeated the private life of 
the imperial family mrs vining also tutored crown prince akihito 
to his fluent english 
at age 15 princess nagako was one of several prospective brides 
selected for hirohito then crown prince 
he chose her over the objections of some powerful court 
officials including the fujiwara family that traditionally supplied 
imperial brides they tried to stop the engagement by producing 
medical records of color blindness in her mothers family but 
doctors disputed the claims and hirohito made it clear he already 
had decided 
once betrothed the couple met only nine times during their 
sixyear engagement the wedding set for 1923 was postponed after 
the great kanto earthquake in september left much of the capital 
burned and in ruins they were wed in an elaborate ceremony on jan 
26 1924 
on christmas day in 1926 nagako became empress of japan when 
hirohito succeeded to the legendary chryanthemum throne on the death 
of his father the taisho emperor 
married longer than any imperial couple in japans history she 
called him okami or honorable master and he affectionately 
referred to her as nagamiya naga from her name and miya 
meaning princess 
she gave birth to seven children the first four were all girls 
and court officials urged hirohito to take a concubine to ensure 
there would be a male heir to the throne 
but the emperor refused and the next child was a boy crown 
prince akihito who was born on dec 23 1933 prince hitachi was 
born in 1935 and a fifth daughter in 1939 
two of their children died a daughter during infancy and the 
eldest child the former princess teru at age 35 in 1961 
the empress enjoys writing 31syllable poems called waka and 
plays the piano violin and koto a 13stringed japanese instrument 
she studied painting under two of japans most respected artists 
signing her work toen or peach garden collections of her works 
have been published in two volumes and an exhibition of her 
drawings was held when she and hirohito traveled to washington in 
1975 
according to custom she spent most of her time with her husband 
and family at the moated imperial palace in central tokyo or their 
mountain and seaside villas 
she kept busy with various indoor duties including newspaper 
clipping for the emperor and keeping track of greetings to foreign 
dignitaries imperial household officials say 
confined by a back ailment and hip problems to a wheelchair the 
empress in recent years has rarely appeared in public but her 
smile graceful wave and devotion to her husband have made her a 
familiar grandmotherly figure to the japanese 
