<TEXT>
emperor hirohito played a major role in ending 
world war ii between japan and the united states according to 
documents in washington archives 
president reagan paid tribute to the actions of hirohito in 
helping to end the the hostilities and leading the japanese people 
through reconstruction after the mikado died on friday 
the japanese account of hirohitos role in the last days of the 
war was first made public when the state department in 1969 issued 
the 1945 volume in its continuing series of us diplomatic 
documents historians regard his acts then as one factor influencing 
the us decision against including the emperor among japanese 
leaders prosecuted for war crimes 
one lengthy report to washington describes the hirohito as 
changing his customary practice of acquiescing in all decisions of 
others to put the brakes on a futile war effort that was out of 
control 
after the collapse of germany it was obvious to japanese leaders 
that the war was lost but the force of militarism and the momentum 
which was carrying the war along were like a bicycle rolling down 
hill without brakes there was no way to stop it and the army itself 
did not know how to give up said the november 1945 account of 
the japanese version of events leading to surrender 
max w bishop a political adviser to gen douglas macarthur the 
supreme allied commander wrote the report quoting a long 
conversation with hisatsune sakomizu who was chief cabinet 
secretary under japans last wartime prime minister kantoro suzuki 
suzuki an admiral had been hirohitos aidedecamp for six 
years and had a personal friendship with the emperor unlike the 
earlier prime minister gen hideki tojo who was later convicted of 
war crimes and hanged 
thus hirohito for the first time was able to express his true 
feelings through the prime minister bishop quoted sakomizu as 
saying 
on august 9 the day nagasaki was bombed in historys second 
atomic attack suzuki decided that nuclear weapons and the soviet 
unions entry into the war provided needed justification for ending 
the conflict the emperor agreed that the war should be brought to 
an end on the basis of the allied potsdam declaration the 
account said 
it continued six top leaders discussed accepting potsdam and 
deadlocked prime minister suzuki the navy and foreign ministers 
favored acceptance provided only that the emperor was retained the 
war minister and the army and navy chiefs of staffs insisted on two 
other conditions that allied forces not occupy japan and that 
japan be allowed to bring home its forces without surrendering them 
abroad 
unable to get the customary consensus suzuki went to the 
emperor who called an imperial conference at 11 pm deadlock 
continued with the prime minister supported 43 
always before it had been the custom for a conference to reach 
a decision without directly involving the emperor but because of 
the close division suzuki asked him to decide said the report 
bishop said sakomizu quoted the mikado as speaking out for peace 
and giving his reasons 
1 from the very start of the war the plans and information of 
the military had been far removed from the facts of the true 
situation 
2 that to continue the war would mean the destruction of the 
japanese people and the country and would also be disastrous to 
world civilization and 
3 termination of the war in this manner at this time was in 
accordance with the will of god and the destiny of the world 
early aug 10 the imperial government messaged acceptance of 
potsdam with the understanding that the emperor would be retained a 
reply three days later said the ultimate form of government would 
depend on the freely expressed will of the japanese people 
suzuki favored immediate final acceptance but most of the 
military again unalterabily opposed hirohito on his own 
initiative called another imperial conference for aug 14 at which 
he asked all to accept his decision to issue an imperial rescript 
ending the war 
it was readied at 11 pm and the emperor decided on his historic 
broadcast directly to the people 
sakomizu also gave details of alreadyknown unsuccessful moves by 
diehard army officers to prevent the broadcast by sealing off the 
palace during the night of august 15 attacking the prime ministers 
official residence and burning the homes of suzuki and baron 
kiichiro hiranuma the privy council president who had favored peace 
on august 16 the stunned populace for the first time heard 
hirohitos voice declare that the war has developed not 
necessarily to japans advantage and was over 
</TEXT>
