<TEXT>
president reagans doctors surgically corrected 
a curvature of his left ring finger on saturday and he was described 
as being in good spirits after the 2hour operation 
the president is comfortable and completed the operation with 
flying colors reagans doctor col john hutton said in a 
statement released by the white house 
the operation was designed to alleviate a rather common but 
deforming condition known as dupuytrens contracture it caused the 
presidents finger to curve inward 
reagans arm will be in a sling and his hand bandaged for several 
days he he will receive no special medication other than routine 
postoperative antibiotics and analgesics the statement said 
it is anticipated that the president will have full use of his 
finger the statement added 
hutton said reagan was alert and responsive throughout the 
surgery which began at 824 am est and was sucessfully 
completed around 11 am est his overall health is excellent 
the physician said 
hes in good spirits white house spokesman marlin fitzwater 
said following the surgery reagan returned to his hospital room 
shortly after the procedure and was visited by his wife nancy the 
spokesman said 
todays procedure is not expected to interrupt the presidents 
normal work schedule fitzwater said 
fitzwater said reagan chatted with the team of physicians 
throughout the procedure talking about horses and his upcoming 
return to california reagan returns to his home state on jan 20 
after presidentelect george bush is inaugurated 
hutton reported that the presidents doctors began administering 
local anesthesia shortly after 730 am to numb his arm and hand 
the procedure was conducted by a team of physicians at walter reed 
army medical center 
hutton said reagans operation consisted of a partial palmer 
and digital fasciectomy the disease extended from the wrist to the 
tip of the ring finger 
fitzwater explained that reagans finger was cut from his palm to 
the tip of his finger and that the diseased tissue was removed in 
order to allow the finger to move freely 
the affliction causes the progressive and usually painless 
contraction of the fingers and is due to a thickening of the tissue 
called fascia in the palm of the hand 
dr robert j neviaser chairman of the orthopedic surgery 
department and director of the hand surgery service at george 
washington university medical center said dupuytrens contraction 
is a fairly common problem in men of irish or scottish ancestry 
reagan is a descendent of irish immigrants 
neviaser said doctors do not know exactly what causes the 
affliction which consists of a cellular activity that changes the 
fascia causing formation of bands and nodules the skin becomes 
thin over the fascia and the contraction of the fingers start 
to relieve the contraction neviaser said surgeons make an 
incision over the area in the palm where a band of tissue has 
formed the fascia is carefully separated from the skin and removed 
the incision in the skin then is stitched back together 
neviaser who is not involved in reagans operation said only 
the tissue directly involved with the finger contraction is removed 
although the procedure to remove the diseased tissue is 
considered minor surgery and patients usually do not remain 
overnight in the hospital reagan was to stay at walter reed until 
sunday as a precaution fitzwater said 
the first lady was expected to stay overnight at the white house 
but to go to the hospital to accompany her husband home 
upon entering the hospital just before noon mrs reagan nodded 
yes when asked if she had spoken with the president by 
telephone flashed a thumbsup signal and said he was fine 
the contracture was minimal when reagan took office in 1981 but 
progressed enough during the past year to require surgical treatment 
untreated the condition eventually may involve all four fingers 
but the thumb leaving the hand in a clenched clawlike position 
fitzwater said hutton did not expect any further surgery to be 
necessary 
after several days the spokesman said reagans splint will be 
removed and he will only be required to wear a hand bandage he will 
wear a socalled dynamic splint for several months it is a 
splint that allows the finger to flex so that the muscles can be 
strengthened the spokesman said 
hutton said the physicians involved besides himself included 
dr george bogumill of georgetown university and a consultant at 
walter reed col alan smith and maj paul perlik of the hand 
service at walter reed 
the anesthesiologist was lt col charles gandy lt col lawrence 
mohr of the white house medical unit and members of the department 
of medicine at walter reed took part as consultants hutton said 
</TEXT>
