a jury has ordered two lawyers to pay a total of 
12 million in damages for mishandling a medical malpractice case 
a baltimore circuit court jury on friday deliberated 45 minutes 
before finding former law partners herbert l singleton jr and 
robert f dashiell negligent in the case brought by arthur and 
shirley stokes whose 16yearold daughter evon died in october 
1974 after minor surgery 
the medical malpractice case originally filed in 1977 was 
dismissed in 1980 for what a judge concluded was a lack of activity 
by the lawyers handling it 
dashiells lawyer charles martinez said his client would 
appeal dashiell has since joined another baltimore law firm 
singleton who represented himself during the trial had his 
legal license suspended indefinitely by the maryland court of 
appeals in february 1986 for neglecting another clients case 
according to stephen snyder an attorney for the stokeses 
singleton admitted deceiving mrs stokes in her daughters case and 
told the jury he had planned to pay her by accumulating money 
through other cases 
evon stokes died after surgery at lutheran hospital to remove a 
cyst from the base of her spine snyder said the surgery should 
have been minor but the girl was given excessive doses of 
anesthesia and died shortly after being taken to the recovery room 
because hospital employees failed to properly monitor her heart 
rate breathing and pulse he said 
the 12 million verdict is the largest legal malpractice award 
given by a jury in maryland snyder said 
in may 1987 the baltimore firm of venable baetjer and howard 
agreed to pay 27 million to settle a legal malpractice lawsuit 
filed by the state of maryland but that sum was not awarded by a 
jury 
