<TEXT>
bestselling author clive cussler led 200 
volunteers saturday in a search for a locomotive believed buried in 
a dry creek bed during an 1878 flood but the hunts first day ended 
with no clues unturned 
cussler said he was not optimistic after workers found only a 
part from a railroad car some tubing and what appeared to be part 
of an old farm wagon 
if i had five guys with magnetometers and lined them up wed 
find it he said but with 200 volunteers its too unwieldy 
none of them have ever worked together before 
the search was to be completed on sunday 
a kansas pacific locomotive reportedly fell 30 feet from a 
railroad bridge along with 19 of its 25 cars and a caboose on the 
night of may 21 1878 when an enormous flood struck the area 30 
miles east of denver twelve of the cars and the locomotive were 
said to have been buried in the sand 
the front brakeman fireman and engineer all were killed 
cussler who lives in golden has become somewhat of a guru to 
people who dream of discovering lost relics through his national 
underwater and marine agency the author of raise the titanic 
has located 54 sunken vessels including a dirigible 
but this is his first buried train 
he said he learned about the train from articles several years 
ago 
i put it away and filed it and i used it for a germ for my 
book night probe he said i brought a psychic out once he 
didnt spot the train but he found a target i had marked 
volunteers used shovels and handheld metal detectors while 
several archeologists and flood experts used a land radar unit to 
search 
some volunteers like curtis hotzinger of denver and his wife 
mary fedoruk said they joined the search because they are fans of 
the writer 
two backhoes dug three large holes in the creekbed in areas 
targeted by metal detectors but water filled the holes about 10 
feet under the surface 
eric walker of darwin australia found the flat car part which 
he described as a horseshoeshaped piece of metal that held a gear 
if the locomotive is found it will belong to the landowner 
cussler said 
since most of the equipment has been donated the cost of the 
search is less than 1000 said agency spokesman craig dirgo 
the town of kiowa near where the tragedy occurred was renamed 
bennett to honor two of the victims widows sisters whose maiden 
names were bennett 
local newspapers reported that about two weeks after the 
accident a man named wolfe londoner searched for the locomotive 
using a magnetized crowbar the rocky mountain news reported that 
the crowbar suddenly plunged violently into the sand dragging 
londoner with it to the astonishment of the spectators 
two hours later londoner reportedly emerged from the bog to 
announce that he had found the missing engine 8 feet under the 
ground and some distance downriver from the bridge however the 
newspaper story doesnt say the locomotive was recovered 
bob richardson director of the colorado railroad museum in 
golden has said he thinks it unlikely that the kansas pacific 
railroad would have left such a large expensive locomotive in the 
sand he said the railroad was in financial straits and human labor 
was cheap at the time the locomotive was said to be worth 18000 
by one account 
however 79yearold emma mitchell whose father was a 
15yearold railroad worker at the time of the flood thinks the 
train is still there 
my father said emphatically that nobody salvaged the 
locomotive she said 
dirgo said the most recent organized search for the train was in 
may 1953 by a colorado school of mines professor they only 
searched an area of 150 by 400 feet and didnt have the kind of 
equipment we have now dirgo said 
