<TEXT>
krzysztof kieslowski the director of a 
short film about killing and a short film about love believes 
the human condition can be expressed by the ways people observe and 
ignore the ten commandments 
the winner of the first european film prize who sees human 
frailty in its purest form has set out to do short films about all 
10 
but anyone expecting nicely packaged sermonettes in kieslowskis 
decalogue will find the effect quite startling 
a short film about killing contains what he believes is the 
longest murder in film history nearly eight minutes of brutality 
that he himself describes as too horrible even for a horror film 
a short film about love speaks equally of loneliness and need 
leaving the viewer scoffing at the superficiality of most 
relationships and rethinking the common assumption that true love 
brings happiness 
long one of polands leading filmmakers kieslowski has remained 
relatively little known in the west but these sophisticated and 
strange tales to use the words of one polish critic may cause 
that to change already they have brought him far more acclaim than 
he ever expected 
killing recently won the first european film award a 
statuette called the felix in west berlin the prize to be 
awarded annually in a different european city is intended to be 
europes answer to the academy awards last may the film won the 
1988 jury award at the cannes film festivallove has been 
submitted as polands entry in the oscars best foreign film 
category 
kieslowski 47 an intense ironic filmmaker whose past work has 
focused on people faced with ambiguous moral and political choices 
has finished shooting the other eight films of his decalogue and is 
editing them for statecontrolled polish tv 
its not a religious inclination to make the decalogue he 
said in an interview its just a look at how difficult it is to 
live how complicated life is 
moses came up with the decalogue 6000 years ago nobody has 
ever questioned it no ideology no politics and yet we violate 
it every day thats interesting 
interesting enough for kieslowski to work harder than he ever has 
in his life he said instead of his usual pace of one film every 
four years he is making 10 in a space of three years 
americans are always saying that if there is something good 
you should shoot it immediately and they are right thats how it 
happened with the decalogue im surprised no one ever thought 
of it earlier 
the first commandment that he completed was the fifth thou shalt 
not kill it resulted in the starkly titled a short film about 
killing the screenplay which kieslowski coauthored with a 
lawyer who is active in political causes portrays the murder of a 
taxi driver by a young criminal and the youths subsequent execution 
for the crime the initial murder lasts seven minutes 44 seconds 
film killing has its own form kieslowski said we know how 
one kills or gets killed in movies unfortunately in real life one 
has to work very hard to kill a man its hard work 
the ruthless hollowcheeked killer played by miroslaw baka 
struggles for what seems an eternity to strangle and beat to death 
the much larger taxi driver and then drag him down a river bank 
strangely by the end of the film which portrays warsaws mean 
streets at their meanest the audience is able to see the killer as 
a victim too 
in poland the film has given impetus to a drive to outlaw 
capital punishment a goal which kieslowski readily endorses 
the movie is against the death penalty because it is against 
killing any form of killing because i think that relations between 
people have become too brutal 
abruptly shifting gears from killing to love kieslowski made a 
haunting film about the crystalline love of an innocent 19yearold 
for a worldly woman in her mid30s whom he observes with the aid of 
a telescope from his room in an apartment block opposite hers 
the film which refers to the sixth commandment ends with their 
positions reversed and the woman longingly watching for the boy 
through the window love fails to bring happiness but afterwards 
they are wiser better people said kieslowski 
the critical acclaim for the films is a complete surprise he 
said 
beginning the screenplays and beginning the production we 
really did not have any idea they would go beyond poland 
kieslowski said 
they are such small films very short cheap films it 
seemed to me they were unusually local although obviously we were 
trying to give them a universal character 
killing is being shown in france and it to be distributed 
throughout europe he said it may eventually be sold to an american 
distributor for the us market 
for polish audiences watching the films there is unflinching 
faithfulness to the realities of life here from a cafe that is out 
of tea at midday to the windswept barren apartment blocks where 
families are packed like so many sardines 
however kieslowski is not striving to portray life in poland but 
values that apply equally everywhere in the world 
its the same experience for an american for a german for a 
frenchman even for a japanese everyone is afraid of death no 
matter what party he belongs to 
he said portraying such elemental universal values was his main 
aim maybe i did not always succeed but i was trying to make them 
in their purest forms 
although critical of polands political system kieslowski has 
continued to work within the statecontrolled film industry rather 
than go abroad or underground but he now avoids political themes in 
his work 
i stopped being interested in politics a long time ago he 
said i hope its for good because it set me free 
</TEXT>
