consumers went on a spending spree in the last 
days of 1988 but while retailers and automakers are basking in the 
glow of impressive sales gains few observers expect their good 
fortune to continue 
the nations biggest retailers had expected only a modestly good 
christmas season following nearly two years of sluggish sales but 
were pleasantly surprised when a lastminute burst of gift buying 
gave them strongerthananticipated results 
analysts estimated the retail industrys december sales rose in a 
range of 6 percent to 75 percent from a year earlier better than 
the 6 percent gain forecast before the start of the holiday season 
meanwhile sales of domesticallyproduced cars and light trucks 
soared 207 percent in the last 10 selling days of the year 
the spurt boosted total sales of cars and light trucks to 1544 
million vehicles in 1988 up from 149 million in 1987 most auto 
industry analysts had estimated us and foreign car makers would 
sell about 145 million cars and light trucks in 1988 
but despite that stellar performance ted sullivan an economist 
