moving higher he said 
were looking for car sales to continue to weaken and they 
have weakened sullivan said noting that while cars sold at an 
annual rate of 108 million cars in early 1988 sales later slipped 
to a rate of 102 million 
auto and retail sales are watched closely as barometers of 
consumer spending which accounts for twothirds of the gross 
national product the broadest measure of the economys growth a 
sharp drop in consumer spending could send the economy into a 
recession 
sales at general merchandise and apparel retailers began to slump 
nearly two years ago although overall consumer spending generally 
increased americans were paying more money for services and 
necessities including cars and so had less money for what 
economists call discretionary spending on items such as 
